What we’ll learn…

  • exposure and confidence. Expectations (google shit!! look for help shit!).
  • we’ll talk about how to THINK about data. Tidy data.
  • messy spreadsheet/cut/paste
  • interactive visualization
  • setup: wanting to break up multivariates, visualize.
  • setup: wanting to track your own memory
  • setup: wanting to collaborate with others, with yourself from other computers. (RStudio server). Take advantage of existing infrastructure.
  • intro to gapminder data set–and relevance to conservation. imagine multivariables in ecology. you’ve got the time variable. field sites? temperature? but also translational.

Here’s an overview of techniques to be covered in Hadley Wickham and Garrett Grolemund of RStudio’s forthcoming book R for Data Science:

Today, we’ll briefly skim across these topics, except for Model:

  • Import: readr to read in simple text files (as comma-seperated values, ie CSV)
  • Tidy: tidyr to organize rows of data into unique values
  • Transform: dplyr to manipulate/wrangle data based on subsetting by rows or columns, sorting and joining
  • Visualise:
    • ggplot2 static plots, using grammar of graphics principles
    • plotly interactive plots, having hover, zoom and pan capabilities
    • tmaps thematic maps, both static and interactive
  • Communicate
    • online website with Github Pages
    • version with git
    • dynamic documents with Rmarkdown
  • how course will run
  • stickynotes, keyboard shortcuts, questions, etc.
